full_text: If a user starts a renewal, then changes the original policy and issues it, what happens to the renewal? If the renewal is unbound, the policy change can be applied to the renewal. In this example of a business owner's policy file, start a renewal manually. The renewal is in the renewal workflow. It will be automatically completed, when it times out on the renewal start date. Go to business owner's line. Verify that the optional coverage is deductible is 500. Go back to the policy file. This time, start a policy change. This time, start a policy change. Click Next to start the process. Go to business owner's line. Change the optional coverage is deductible. Select 1000. Quote the policy change. Issue the policy. Note a message about a later unbound renewal. You can apply the changes to the renewal by clicking the message link. The renewal job is put back in draft mode. Go to business owner's line. Verify that the previous policy change date of 1000 on optional coverage is deductible has been applied to the renewal job. You must quote the renewal again. Click Bind Options. Select Renew. Select a renewal code. Click OK to save the data. The renewal is put back to the automatic renewal workflow and is in a renewing status. This is the end of demonstration of interrupted renewal. Click the plan of bankruptcy.                           so
